{"doc": "older workers are suffering dismal pay rises while those awarded to the youngest workers have gone up by nine times as much\nthe gap between wage rises for young and older staff has widened significantly during the past five years , amid claims the over- 50s are being left behind , official figures reveal\ncritics said employers were cynically taking advantage of older workers who stay with the same company for longer by failing to train and promote them or give them decent annual pay rises\nthe under - 25s saw their wages rise more than eight times faster than the over- 50s , as they quickly climbed the rungs of the career ladder last year , workers aged 18 to 24 received bumper 10.6 per cent pay rises , falling to 3.8 per cent for people aged 25 to 34 and to 2 per cent for workers aged 36 to 49\nfor workers aged 50 to 64 , pay rises plunge to a meagre 1.2 per cent , official figures show â significantly below the britain average of 2.1 per cent\nthe ons revealed in its latest economic review that the under - 25s are five times as likely to have moved jobs in the past three months than workers over- 50\nbut while younger workers often receive greater pay rises because they move jobs more frequently , official data shows that the gap is widening\nin 2009 , britain âs youngest workers received pay rises three times greater than older workers , but this has now widened to nine times greater\nin the last three months of 2014 , 5.4 per cent of 18 - 25 - year - olds changed jobs , compared to only 1.2 per cent of 50 - 64 - year - olds experts said the growing gulf between the generations could signal a reluctance by employers to train and promote older members of staff\nros altmann , a whitehall adviser on older workers , said : â younger people âs pay is rising faster than average and the rate of increase is accelerating\nâ it could be because younger people are the most likely to receive training , with employers keen to focus on the newer workers an